{"title_page": "Aouzou Strip", "text_new": "{{redirect|Aouzou|the town in Chad|Aouzou, Chad}}\n\n[[Image:Map of Aouzou stip chad-svg.svg|thumb|upright|The Aouzou strip shown in red]]\n\nThe '''Aouzou Strip''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u028a|z|u\u02d0}}; {{lang-ar|\u0642\u0637\u0627\u0639 \u0623\u0648\u0632\u0648}} ''Qi\u1e6d\u0101\u02bf Awz\u016b'', {{lang-fr|Bande d'Aozou}}) is a strip of land in northern [[Chad]] which lies along the border with [[Libya]], extending south to a depth of about 100 kilometers into Chad's [[Borkou-Ennedi-Tibesti Region]] for an area of 114,000&nbsp;km\u00b2 and is named after the small town and [[oasis]] [[Aouzou, Chad|Aouzou]]. The region played a significant role in the [[Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]].\n\n==Inclusion in Italian Libya==\n[[File:Chad-Libya border 1935 (Aouzou Strip).png|thumb|300 px|Detailed 1935 map of the Aouzou Strip]]\nThe Aouzou strip was defined for the first time in the discussions between France and Italy after [[World War I]], in relation to an award to Italy for the victory in that war.  At the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919]], the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]] did not receive any of the [[German Empire|German]] colonies, but instead was given the [[Oltre Giuba]] from the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], and France agreed to give some Saharan territories to [[Italian Libya]].\n\nAfter many discussions during the 1920s, in 1935 the [[Franco-Italian Agreement]] was signed between [[Benito Mussolini]] and [[Pierre Laval]], which included a provision under which Italy would receive the Aouzou strip, which was to be added to Libya.<ref name=\"locked\">Hodder, Lloyd, McLachlan (1998). ''Land-locked states of Africa and Asia, Volume 2'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=dGjh1GGRlagC&pg=PA32 p. 32]. Frank Cass, London, Great Britain.</ref> France's other motivations in concluding this agreement with Italy were to settle the status of the [[Italian Tunisians|Italian Tunisian community]] in its [[French protectorate of Tunisia|protectorate of the country]], to remove [[Italia irredenta|irredentist Italian claims]] to [[Nice]], and to prevent Italy from growing closer to Nazi Germany by keeping it closely aligned with France and the United Kingdom (the [[Stresa Front]]).<ref name=\"locked\"/>\n\nThis policy failed two years later after Italy drifted into the German orbit by concluding the [[Pact of Steel]] with Nazi Germany, leading to the \"instruments of ratification\" of the Mussolini-Laval Treaty never being exchanged with France.<ref name=\"locked\"/> Despite this the new border was conventionally assumed to be the southern boundary of Libya until 1955.<ref name=\"locked\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nClaimed to be rich in [[uranium]] deposits,<ref name='crs_libya_brief'>[https://fpc.state.gov/documents/organization/9577.pdf Libya Issue Brief], [[Congressional Research Service]] ([[US State Department]]). April 10, 2002.</ref> the area was the cause of dispute with Libya, which led to a war between the two countries. In 1973, Libya engaged in military operations in the Aouzou Strip to gain access to minerals and to use it as a base of influence in Chadian politics. This ultimately resulted in the [[Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]].\n\nLibya argued that the territory was inhabited by indigenous people who owed vassalage to the [[Sanusiya Order|Senoussi Order]] and subsequently to the [[Ottoman Empire]], and that this title had been inherited by Libya. It also supported its claim with an unratified 1935 treaty between [[French Third Republic|France]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] (the ''[[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]]-[[Pierre Laval|Laval]] Treaty''), the [[colonial power]]s of Chad and Libya, respectively, that confirmed the possession of the strip by Italy.\n\nThe frontier claimed by the Chadian government was based on a 1955 treaty between France and Libya, which, in turn, referred back to an 1899 agreement between [[United Kingdom|Great Britain]] and France about \"spheres of influence\".  Despite other differences, this was one position on which all Chadian political parties and factions were able to agree.\n\nDuring the so-called [[Toyota War]] in 1987, the final stage of the Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict, Chadian forces were able to force the Libyans to retreat from the Aouzou Strip. A cease-fire between Chad and Libya held from 1987 to 1988, followed by unsuccessful negotiations over the next several years. Finally a 1994 [[International Court of Justice]] [[Case Concerning the Territorial Dispute (Libyan Arab Jamahiriya/Chad)|decision]] found (by a majority of 16 to 1) in favour of Chad sovereignty over the Aouzou strip, and ended the Libyan claim.\n\nThe [[United Nations Security Council]] established the United Nations Aouzou Strip Observer Group in [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 915|Resolution 915]] (May 1994) to monitor the withdrawal of Libyan troops, and terminated it in [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 926|Resolution 926]] (June 1994), when the withdrawal  was completed.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Franco-Italian Agreement of 1935|Mussolini\u2013Laval accord]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140220195334/http://www.icj-cij.org/docket/index.php?p1=3&p2=3&code=dt&case=83&k=cd Territorial Dispute (Libyan Arab Jamahiriya/Chad)] \u2013 The case documents on [[International Court of Justice|ICJ]] website\n* Frank Jacobs: [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/07/the-worlds-largest-sandbox/ Borderlines: The World\u2019s Largest Sandbox], The New York Times / The Opinion Pages on November 7, 2011\n\n{{Countries and territories of North Africa |state=collapsed}}\n{{Italian Libya}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Chad]]\n[[Category:Geography of Libya]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Chad]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Libya]]\n[[Category:Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]]\n[[Category:Chad\u2013Libya border]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Aouzou|the town in Chad|Aouzou, Chad}}\n\n[[Image:Map of Aouzou stip chad-svg.svg|thumb|upright|The Aouzou strip shown in red]]\n\nThe '''Aouzou Strip''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u028a|z|u\u02d0}}; Arabic \u0642\u0637\u0627\u0639 \u0623\u0648\u0632\u0648 ''Qi\u1e6d\u0101\u02bf Awz\u016b'', {{lang-fr|Bande d'Aozou}}) is a strip of land in northern [[Chad]] which lies along the border with [[Libya]], extending south to a depth of about 100 kilometers into Chad's [[Borkou-Ennedi-Tibesti Region]] for an area of 114,000&nbsp;km\u00b2 and is named after the small town and [[oasis]] [[Aouzou, Chad|Aouzou]]. The region played a significant role in the [[Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]].\n\n==Inclusion in Italian Libya==\n[[File:Chad-Libya border 1935 (Aouzou Strip).png|thumb|300 px|Detailed 1935 map of the Aouzou Strip]]\nThe Aouzou strip was defined for the first time in the discussions between France and Italy after [[World War I]], in relation to an award to Italy for the victory in that war.  At the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919]], the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]] did not receive any of the [[German Empire|German]] colonies, but instead was given the [[Oltre Giuba]] from the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], and France agreed to give some Saharan territories to [[Italian Libya]].\n\nAfter many discussions during the 1920s, in 1935 the [[Franco-Italian Agreement]] was signed between [[Benito Mussolini]] and [[Pierre Laval]], which included a provision under which Italy would receive the Aouzou strip, which was to be added to Libya.<ref name=\"locked\">Hodder, Lloyd, McLachlan (1998). ''Land-locked states of Africa and Asia, Volume 2'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=dGjh1GGRlagC&pg=PA32 p. 32]. Frank Cass, London, Great Britain.</ref> France's other motivations in concluding this agreement with Italy were to settle the status of the [[Italian Tunisians|Italian Tunisian community]] in its [[French protectorate of Tunisia|protectorate of the country]], to remove [[Italia irredenta|irredentist Italian claims]] to [[Nice]], and to prevent Italy from growing closer to Nazi Germany by keeping it closely aligned with France and the United Kingdom (the [[Stresa Front]]).<ref name=\"locked\"/>\n\nThis policy failed two years later after Italy drifted into the German orbit by concluding the [[Pact of Steel]] with Nazi Germany, leading to the \"instruments of ratification\" of the Mussolini-Laval Treaty never being exchanged with France.<ref name=\"locked\"/> Despite this the new border was conventionally assumed to be the southern boundary of Libya until 1955.<ref name=\"locked\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nClaimed to be rich in [[uranium]] deposits,<ref name='crs_libya_brief'>[https://fpc.state.gov/documents/organization/9577.pdf Libya Issue Brief], [[Congressional Research Service]] ([[US State Department]]). April 10, 2002.</ref> the area was the cause of dispute with Libya, which led to a war between the two countries. In 1973, Libya engaged in military operations in the Aouzou Strip to gain access to minerals and to use it as a base of influence in Chadian politics. This ultimately resulted in the [[Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]].\n\nLibya argued that the territory was inhabited by indigenous people who owed vassalage to the [[Sanusiya Order|Senoussi Order]] and subsequently to the [[Ottoman Empire]], and that this title had been inherited by Libya. It also supported its claim with an unratified 1935 treaty between [[French Third Republic|France]] and [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] (the ''[[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]]-[[Pierre Laval|Laval]] Treaty''), the [[colonial power]]s of Chad and Libya, respectively, that confirmed the possession of the strip by Italy.\n\nThe frontier claimed by the Chadian government was based on a 1955 treaty between France and Libya, which, in turn, referred back to an 1899 agreement between [[United Kingdom|Great Britain]] and France about \"spheres of influence\".  Despite other differences, this was one position on which all Chadian political parties and factions were able to agree.\n\nDuring the so-called [[Toyota War]] in 1987, the final stage of the Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict, Chadian forces were able to force the Libyans to retreat from the Aouzou Strip. A cease-fire between Chad and Libya held from 1987 to 1988, followed by unsuccessful negotiations over the next several years. Finally a 1994 [[International Court of Justice]] [[Case Concerning the Territorial Dispute (Libyan Arab Jamahiriya/Chad)|decision]] found (by a majority of 16 to 1) in favour of Chad sovereignty over the Aouzou strip, and ended the Libyan claim.\n\nThe [[United Nations Security Council]] established the United Nations Aouzou Strip Observer Group in [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 915|Resolution 915]] (May 1994) to monitor the withdrawal of Libyan troops, and terminated it in [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 926|Resolution 926]] (June 1994), when the withdrawal  was completed.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Franco-Italian Agreement of 1935|Mussolini\u2013Laval accord]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140220195334/http://www.icj-cij.org/docket/index.php?p1=3&p2=3&code=dt&case=83&k=cd Territorial Dispute (Libyan Arab Jamahiriya/Chad)] \u2013 The case documents on [[International Court of Justice|ICJ]] website\n* Frank Jacobs: [http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/11/07/the-worlds-largest-sandbox/ Borderlines: The World\u2019s Largest Sandbox], The New York Times / The Opinion Pages on November 7, 2011\n\n{{Countries and territories of North Africa |state=collapsed}}\n{{Italian Libya}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Chad]]\n[[Category:Geography of Libya]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Chad]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Libya]]\n[[Category:Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]]\n[[Category:Chad\u2013Libya border]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aouzou_Strip"}
{"title_page": "1999\u20132000 Leeds United A.F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2010}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| season             = [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000]]\n| manager            = [[David O'Leary]]\n| chairman           = [[Peter Ridsdale]]\n| stadium            = [[Elland Road]]\n| league             = [[Premier League]]\n| league result      = [[1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|3rd]]\n| cup1               = [[FA Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = [[1999\u20132000 FA Cup#Fifth round proper|Fifth round]]\n| cup2               = [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = [[1999\u20132000 Football League Cup|Fourth round]]\n| cup3               = [[UEFA Cup]]\n| cup3 result        = [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|Semi-finals]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Michael Bridges]] (19)\n| season topscorer   = Michael Bridges (21)\n| highest attendance = 40,192 vs [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]  <br> <small>(25 September 1999, [[FA Premier League|Premier League]])</small>\n| lowest attendance  = 11,912 vs [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] <br> <small>(12 December 1999, [[FA Cup]])</small>\n| average attendance = 37,579\n| prevseason         = [[1998\u201399 Leeds United A.F.C. season|1998\u201399]]\n| nextseason         = [[2000\u201301 Leeds United A.F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n}}\n\nDuring the '''[[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000 season]]''', '''[[Leeds United A.F.C.]]''' competed in the [[FA Premier League]] (known as the FA Carling Premiership for sponsorship reasons).\n\n==Season summary==\nAfter an exiting previous season good times looked to be on the horizon for David O'Leary and his young team in his first full season in charge, despite loosing previous seasons top scorer Jimmy-Floyd Hassilbaink and a tough start Leeds begin winning and scoring regularly and quickly stormed top of the Premiership, United entered the new millennium still top and also progressing in the Uafer cup, but an off the filed incident involving star players Lee Bowyer and Johnathan Woodgate combined with the small and young squad effected Leeds form in the new year where United lost ground to leaders[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. Never the less Leeds regained form and were closing in on the [[UEFA Cup]] final but again off the filed incidents plagued the team, before kick off violence saw two Leeds fans stabbed to death after a clash between rival supporters]] on the eve of semi-final against [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]]. Leeds were never the same side that night and would be knocked out in the semi final, On the more positive side, Leeds finished 3rd their highest finish since the 1992 title triumph, and achieved [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] qualification in manager [[David O'Leary]]'s second season at the helm. Promising young players like [[Alan Smith (footballer born 1980)|Alan Smith]], [[Jonathan Woodgate]] and [[Michael Bridges]] gave Leeds fans hope that their side would be among [[2000-01 in English football|next season's]] contenders for the Premiership, as well as making another strong challenge on the continent. Australian midfielder, [[Harry Kewell]], announced his arrival to the Premiership by winning the [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] award.\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|1999\u20132000 FA Premier League}}\n{{:1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|showteam=LEE}}\n\n;Results summary\n{{Fb_rs|hw=12|hd=2|hl=5|hgf=29|hga=18|aw=9|ad=4|al=6|agf=29|aga=25}}\n{{Fb_rs_footer|s=[http://www.soccerbase.com/tournaments/tournament.sd?tourn_id=114 1999-2000 FA Premier League table]|date=December 2014}}\n\n;Results by round\n{{#invoke:sports rbr table|table|legendpos=b\n|header=Round\n|label1= Ground\n| res1=H/A/A/H/H/A/A/H/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/H/A/A/H/A/H/A/A/H/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/H/A/A/H/H/A\n|la